---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="From Robot Runtime to Climate Sensor — OpenCastor Blog"
  description="How OpenCastor robots are donating idle AI compute to climate modeling, biodiversity monitoring, protein folding, and humanitarian AI."
  ogUrl="https://opencastor.com/blog/contribute-to-science"
>

<main>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="page-hero" style="padding-bottom:24px">
    <p class="section-label reveal">Blog</p>
    <h1 class="reveal reveal-d1" style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto">From Robot Runtime to Climate Sensor:<br><span class="gradient-text">How OpenCastor Robots Are Donating Idle Compute to Science</span></h1>
    <p class="reveal reveal-d2" style="font-size:0.9rem;color:var(--text-muted);margin-top:16px">March 19, 2026 &middot; Craig Merry</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ARTICLE -->
  <section class="section" style="padding-top:0">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px">

      <!-- The spark -->
      <div class="wizard-tip reveal" style="margin-bottom:32px">
        <p style="font-style:italic;font-size:1.05rem;line-height:1.7;margin:0">"How long before someone launches SETI@Home but the AGI era?"</p>
        <p style="margin:8px 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          &mdash; Chris Albon (<a href="https://x.com/chrisalbon" style="color:var(--accent)">@chrisalbon</a>), Director of ML at Wikimedia Foundation<br>
          <a href="https://x.com/chrisalbon/status/2034653589755559997" style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:0.8rem">March 19, 2026</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        When Chris posted this, we were sitting in front of a Raspberry Pi 5 with a Hailo-8L NPU strapped to it.
        The robot it controls &mdash; Bob, our reference platform &mdash; was idle. Had been for twenty minutes. Its 26 TOPS
        neural processor was doing absolutely nothing, burning about 2 watts for the privilege of being ready.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        That question landed differently for us. We're not building a cloud service or an app &mdash; we're building
        the runtime layer for physical robots that already have AI accelerators, cameras, and microphones deployed
        in the real world. The answer to Chris's question isn't "someone should build that." It's: we already have the hardware. We just need to use it.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        So we built <code>castor contribute</code>.
      </p>

      <!-- SETI@Home parallel -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The SETI@Home parallel</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        SETI@Home ran from 1999 to 2020. At its peak, 5.2 million volunteers donated their home PCs to search
        for extraterrestrial intelligence. The model worked: Folding@home later proved it could do real science,
        contributing to COVID-19 research by simulating protein dynamics across millions of consumer CPUs and GPUs.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        But here's what's different in 2026: the nodes aren't just CPUs anymore. An OpenCastor robot is a
        multimodal AI node with a neural processing unit, a depth camera, a microphone, and physical presence
        in a real environment. That's not just compute &mdash; it's situated intelligence. A robot on a farm can
        listen for bird calls. A robot in a school can classify local weather patterns from its camera feed.
        The sensor data <em>is</em> the science.
      </p>

      <!-- What robots have -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">What OpenCastor robots have</h2>

      <div class="bento reveal" style="grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:16px;margin-bottom:32px">
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">Hailo-8L NPU</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">26 TOPS at ~2W. Purpose-built for edge AI inference &mdash; image classification, object detection, audio models.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">OAK-D Depth Camera</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Stereo depth + RGB. Real-time vision processing for species identification, satellite imagery ground-truth, anomaly detection.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">Microphone</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Audio classification at ~0.1W. BirdNET bioacoustics, environmental sound monitoring, acoustic anomaly detection.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="padding:20px">
          <h3 style="font-size:1rem;margin:0 0 8px">Physical Presence</h3>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Deployed in homes, schools, farms, labs. Distributed sensor network that traditional compute clusters can never be.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- The idle compute problem -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The idle compute problem</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        A robot waiting for its next command is burning ~3W but producing zero useful work. Bob idles for
        about 20 hours a day. That's 520 TOPS-hours of wasted neural compute, every single day, from one robot.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Scale that to a fleet. 1,000 robots &times; 8 hours idle/day &times; 26 TOPS = 208,000 TOPS-hours/day.
        That's the equivalent of a small GPU cluster, but physically distributed across real-world environments
        where it can collect and process data that centralized servers never could.
      </p>

      <!-- What castor contribute does -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">What <code>castor contribute</code> does</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        The feature is dead simple. Add a block to your RCAN config:
      </p>

      <div class="code-block reveal" style="margin-bottom:24px">
        <div class="code-header">
          <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
          <span class="code-filename">robot.rcan.yaml</span>
        </div>
        <div class="code-body">
<span class="k">agent</span>:
  <span class="k">contribute</span>:
    <span class="k">enabled</span>: <span class="s">true</span>
    <span class="k">idle_after_minutes</span>: <span class="s">15</span>
    <span class="k">projects</span>:
      - <span class="s">climate</span>
      - <span class="s">biodiversity</span>
      - <span class="s">science</span>
    <span class="k">coordinator</span>: <span class="s">boinc</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        After 15 minutes of idle time, the robot contacts a work coordinator (BOINC, Folding@home, or
        OpenCastor's own coordinator for sensor-based projects). It fetches a work unit, runs it on the
        Hailo NPU or CPU, and submits the result. The moment a real command comes in &mdash; a chat message,
        a movement instruction, anything &mdash; the contribute work is cancelled within 100ms and the robot
        returns to full duty.
      </p>

      <!-- Use cases -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">Use cases by domain</h2>

      <div class="reveal" style="margin-bottom:32px">
        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-bottom:8px">Climate</h3>
        <p style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          Satellite imagery classification for deforestation monitoring. Federated climate model training
          where each robot contributes local gradient updates without sharing raw data. Ground-truth weather
          observation from cameras deployed in the field.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:8px">Biodiversity</h3>
        <p style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          BirdNET bioacoustics via the onboard microphone &mdash; robots in gardens and parks passively
          monitoring bird populations at near-zero energy cost. OAK-D depth camera for insect and plant
          species identification. This is science that only makes sense with distributed physical sensors.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:8px">Science</h3>
        <p style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          Folding@home-style protein structure prediction on the Hailo NPU. Rosetta@home work units compiled
          to HEF format for efficient edge inference. Each robot contributes a small piece of a massive
          distributed computation.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:8px">Humanitarian AI</h3>
        <p style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
          Medical image pre-screening for WHO and MSF deployments. Chest X-ray classification for TB screening
          in resource-limited settings. Edge inference means results are available in-country without sending
          patient data to the cloud.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Fleet math -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The fleet math</h2>

      <div class="reveal" style="margin-bottom:24px">
        <table class="arch-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Fleet Size</th><th>Daily Idle Hours</th><th>TOPS-Hours/Day</th><th>Equivalent</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>1 robot</td><td>8h</td><td>208</td><td>&mdash;</td></tr>
            <tr><td>100 robots</td><td>8h</td><td>20,800</td><td>Small workstation GPU</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1,000 robots</td><td>8h</td><td>208,000</td><td>Small GPU cluster</td></tr>
            <tr><td>10,000 robots</td><td>8h</td><td>2,080,000</td><td>Large research cluster</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        The numbers aren't about raw FLOPS competing with an H100. They're about something no GPU cluster has:
        physical distribution. Ten thousand robots in ten thousand locations, each with a camera, a microphone,
        and an NPU. That's a planetary sensor network that does science when it's not doing robotics.
      </p>

      <!-- P66 safety -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">Safety first, always</h2>

      <div class="wizard-tip reveal" style="margin-bottom:24px">
        <strong>Protocol 66 guarantee:</strong> Contribute work is immediately preempted by any incoming command.
        A robot helping fold proteins will drop everything the moment a user sends a message. The P66 safety protocol
        takes absolute precedence &mdash; the robot signals <code>ContributeCancel</code> to the coordinator and
        becomes available within 100ms. This is enforced at the kernel level and cannot be disabled by configuration.
      </div>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        We designed this from the start as a background citizen, not a competing process. The contribute scheduler
        checks for active commands before every work unit fetch. If your robot is needed, it's yours instantly.
        Science gets the leftovers &mdash; which, in a fleet of idle robots, turns out to be a lot.
      </p>

      <!-- Closing -->
      <h2 class="reveal" style="font-size:1.75rem;margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:16px">The AGI-era SETI@Home starts here</h2>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Chris Albon asked how long before someone launches SETI@Home for the AGI era. The answer is: the infrastructure
        already exists. Every OpenCastor robot has an AI accelerator that idles most of the day. We just had to
        connect the idle cycles to the people who need them.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        This is version one. We're starting with BOINC integration and BirdNET bioacoustics. Climate@Home and
        WHO-TB screening are in the pipeline. If you're a researcher with a distributed inference problem that
        fits on a 26 TOPS NPU, we want to hear from you.
      </p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-size:1.0625rem;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text-secondary)">
        Your robot is already awake. Let's put it to work.
      </p>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="reveal" style="margin-top:48px;padding:32px;background:var(--bg-card);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:12px;text-align:center">
        <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem;margin-bottom:16px">Enable contribute on your robot</h3>
        <div class="code-block" style="max-width:400px;margin:0 auto 20px">
          <div class="code-header">
            <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
            <span class="code-filename">Terminal</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-body">castor contribute start</div>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center">
          <a href="/docs/contribute" class="btn btn-primary">Read the docs</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/craigm26/OpenCastor" class="btn btn-secondary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View on GitHub</a>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</main>

<style>
  .arch-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
  }
  .arch-table th {
    text-align: left;
    padding: 8px 12px;
    background: var(--alt-bg);
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border);
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .arch-table td {
    padding: 8px 12px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  .arch-table tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
</style>

</BaseLayout>
